CartService is a downstream dependency for several upstream calls. Given its increased latency, it is plausible that delays propagate upstream affecting other callers like Frontend.\n\n### Conclusion\nThe hypothesis is supported by the trace findings. There is a clear correlation between the observed delay multiplier and the error rates associated with CartService. The latency and error rates strongly point towards it being a contributing factor to the fault and indicate the necessity of investigating CartService and its interaction with Redis in further detail.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"stance\": \"SUPPORT\",\n  \"detected_trace_keys\": [\"rrt_max\", \"frontend->cartservice\", \"error_ratio\"],\n  \"hypotheses\": [\n    {\n      \"component\": \"CartService\",\n      \"reason\": \"rrt_max\",\n      \"evidence\": \"The delay multiplier for Frontend to CartService calls was approximately 4.16 times the normal average duration during the anomaly period.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"component\": \"CartService\",\n      \"reason\": \"error_ratio\",\n      \"evidence\": \"Significant error rate peaking at around 24.8%, likely contributing to overall system instability.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThe hypothesis that CartService is the root cause is supported by significant latency and high error rates detected during the anomaly period. This warrants focused scrutiny on CartService's interactions, particularly with its dependencies like Redis, to rectify identified performance issues."}
